elopment, build, and testing of Starship. These costs consist of:\n*   Test flight hardware and Raptor engines (which are expensed when used in test flights).\n*   Employee compensation costs (salaries, benefits, share-based compensation).\n*   Tooling and equipment expenses.\n*   Depreciation for R&D equipment.\n*   Allocated overhead.\n\n**Accounting Treatment and Future Expectations:**\nBecause Starship is currently in the development stage, a majority of its costs are expensed to Research and Development as incurred. The company expects Space R&D to continue increasing in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue throughout 2026 as development and commercialization efforts accelerate. \n\nOnce Starship is commercialized (defined as delivering payload to orbit), the company expects R&D spending to moderate. At the point of commercialization, Starship costs will generally shift from being expensed as R&D to being capitalized and depreciated in the cost of revenue of the segment associated with the payload delivered.',
