2026-06-25 03:50:58,828 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Answer\n\n### 1. Connectivity Revenue as % of Consolidated Q1 2026 Revenue\n\nFrom the SpaceX S-1 reportable segment financial information table (three months ended March 31, 2026):\n\n| Segment | Q1 2026 Revenue ($M) |\n|---|---|\n| Space | 619 |\n| **Connectivity** | **3,257** |\n| AI | 818 |\n| **Total consolidated revenue** | **4,694** |\n\n**Calculation:** $3,257M ÷ $4,694M = **69.39%**\n\nConnectivity revenue represented approximately **69.39%** of consolidated Q1 2026 revenue.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Quarters of Starship R&D Spending Equal to One Year of FY2025 Connectivity Capex\n\nFrom the S-1 disclosures:\n\n- **FY2025 Connectivity segment capital expenditures:** $4,178M\n- **Q1 2026 Starship R&D expense (funded by the Space segment):** $930M\n\n**Calculation:** $4,178M ÷ $930M = **4.49 quarters**\n\nApproximately **4.49 quarters** (roughly 13.5 months) of current Starship R&D spending would equal one year of FY2025 Connectivity capex. In other words, Starship R&D is currently running at a quarterly pace (~$930M) that is only modestly below the entire annual Connectivity capex base (~$4,178M).\n\n---\n\n### 3. Which Metric Better Captures Cross-Segment Dependency?\n\n**The second metric (Starship R&D vs. Connectivity capex) better captures cross-segment dependency.**\n\nReasoning:\n\n- **The first metric (Connectivity revenue share of consolidated revenue)** measures *revenue concentration* — i.e., how much consolidated revenue depends on a single segment. It is a within-segment / portfolio-concentration metric, not a cross-segment dependency metric. It tells you that Connectivity is the dominant revenue contributor, but it says nothing about how segments interact with or depend on one another.\n\n- **The second metric (Starship R&D vs. Connectivity capex)** directly links investment in one segment (Space — Starship development) to the capital base of another segment (Connectivity). The S-1 explicitly describes Starship as the "key enabler of our long-term growth strategy" that will unlock new mission categories and reduce the cost to reach orbit by 99% or more — including enabling cheaper deployment of Starlink satellites (Connectivity) and future orbital AI compute (AI segment). The fact that ~4.5 quarters of Starship R&D equals an entire year of Connectivity capex quantifies the *relative scale of investment in the enabling technology (Starship) versus the dependent segment\'s infrastructure (Starlink ground/space assets)*. This is a genuine cross-segment dependency signal: the Space segment\'s R&D outlays are, in effect, subsidizing the long-term economics of the Connectivity (and AI) segments.\n\nIn short, the revenue-share metric captures *consolidation concentration*, while the Starship-R&D-to-Connectivity-capex ratio captures *cross-segment investment dependency* — the latter being the more analytically relevant measure of how segments depend on one another.\n\n---\n\n### Important Context\n\nPer the filing, the consolidated financial statements have been retrospectively recast under common-control accounting to include xAI (merged February 2, 2026) and X Holdings (merged into xAI March 28, 2025) for all historical periods presented. No period reflects standalone SpaceX operations exclusively. The Q1 2026 figures above reflect the recast consolidated entity (Space + Connectivity + AI segments).\n\n---\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026) — Reportable Segment Financial Information; Capital Expenditures by Segment; Starship R&D disclosures"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
